$ PowerShell: String manipulation operators

→ Windows/PowerShell/language/operator[PowerShell operators] for string manipulation are `-join`, `-split`, `-replace`…

{ -replace #ps-replace

  `-replace` replaces a (sub-string) of a string or a string array with another string. → development/regular-expressions[Regular expressions] are possible.

  gh|about-PowerShell|/language/operator/string-manipulation/replace.ps1||

}
{ -split / -join #ps-split-join

 → Windows/PowerShell/language/operator/string-manipulation/split[`-split`] creates an → Windows/PowerShell/language/type/array[array] from a string, `-join` creates a string from an array.

  gh|about-PowerShell|/language/operator/string-manipulation/split-join.ps1||

  `-split` and `-join` behave very much like the Perl functions → development/languages/Perl/functions/split[`split()`] and
  → development/languages/Perl/functions/join[`join()`].

  Note that the `-join` operator can also be used to → Windows/PowerShell/language/type/string/concatenate[concatenate strings].

}
